Functionalizing NEON raster data

Sarah Graves

June 21, 2016

Ojbectives

Start by putting up objectives/tasks that students will be working though:

  1. Import a raster A lidar canopy height model (lidar/Teak_lidarCHM.tif)
  2. For the CHM, set values == 0 to NA (not trees)
  3. Visualize density and plot vertical cutoff lines.
  4. Classify the raster according to some distribution low medium and tall trees. This could be done using a histogram potentially or we could just decide that <2m is generally grasses / understory, <6m small trees,and the rest are tall trees. A function could import the desired thresholds. Visualize histogram/density and plot vertical cutoff lines.
  5. Take the chm and create a hillshade (http://neon-workwithdata.github.io/neon-data-institute-2016/R/create-hillshade-R/)
  6. Plot the classified raster, add a legend for each class - legends are super tricky to simplifying this process with a function would be good. see: http://neon-workwithdata.github.io/neon-data-institute-2016/R/classify-by-threshold-R/ for my take on forcing a legend outside of the plot area using par settings. You may have other better forms of magic to make this work well. :)
  7. Export the plot figure to a pdf publishable
  8. Export the classified raster as a geotiff with NaFlagg = -9999 to an outputs folder.

Load packages

library(raster)

Import raster

chm <- raster("../NEONdata/D17-California/TEAK/2013/lidar/TEAK_lidarCHM.tif")
plot(chm)

Set NA values

# view data to see zero values
plot(chm==0)

hist(chm)
## Warning in .hist1(x, maxpixels = maxpixels, main = main, plot = plot, ...):
## 32% of the raster cells were used. 100000 values used.

# assign NA to zeros because we don't want to analyze zero values (it's not vegetation)
chm[chm==0] <- NA

# check to see if zeros are removed
hist(chm)

Set class breaks

Classify the CHM to differentiate between trees and non-trees. Trees will be those above some threshold.

hist(chm)

# set threshold value
thresh <- c(3,20)

hist(chm)
abline(v=thresh,col="blue")

Classify raster

class.m <- c(0,thresh[1],1,
             thresh[1],thresh[2],2,
             thresh[2],max(chm@data@values,na.rm = T),3)

# reshape the object into a matrix with columns and rows
rcl.m <- matrix(class.m,
                nrow=3,
                byrow = T)

# reclassify the raster using the reclass object - rcl.m
chm.class <- reclassify(chm,
                        rcl.m)

plot(chm.class,
     main="CHM classified by height thresholds")
